text:
i'm thinking about adding elecro- luminescent wire into my bag-o-tricks. what would you think of elwire tracing a pair of lips, like the one i posted a few days ago?
.
last night, i wrote my name in pencil on canvas, and traced it in wire. between my 1st & last name i poked the wire through the canvas.
.
no matter what, i'm going to use this wire for night time messaging. i've been doing music festivals that only get better after dark! (and i bring blow-up couches!) i want to make something reminiscent of a "cheesy" neon motel sign, just to "make light" of the stereotype of nudity automatically leading to sex. maybe some animated boobs? #mondaymotivation

text:
i was ashamed. i was afraid nobody would believe me. i wanted to forget it ever happened. these are just a few statements echoed across the hundreds of thousands of tweets using the hashtag #whyididntreport, a new movement that has taken the internet by storm. in a matter of days, hundreds of thousands of people contributed, collectively shedding light on the countless reasons that sexual assault survivors choose not to formally report their abuses.
*
while hashtag movements seem to have sprung up rather recently, according to dr. jessalynn keller, phd, professor in the department of communication, media and film, movements including #metoo and #whyididntreport are part of the age-old practice of consciousness-raising. â€œconsciousness-raising is about sharing individual stories and linking them to a broader social structure,â€ keller explains.
â€œhashtags are new in the sense that the technology itself is new, but the idea behind these movements â€” sharing oneâ€™s story to validate it, to make it real and to have your voice heard â€” is a historical practice that women have been using for decades to illuminate larger problems and social inequalities.â€
*
keller highlights that movements like #whyididntreport are particularly compelling because of the human and emotional elements inherent in storytelling. learn more on arts.ucalgary.ca
*
if you think you have experienced sexual violence, or know someone who has, visit the sexual violence support website for campus and community resources: ucalgary.ca/sexualviolencesupport. you can also arrange a confidential consultation with carla bertsch, the universityâ€™s sexual violence support advocate, by confidential email: svsa@ucalgary.ca

dear good guys,
hello. 
the first thing you need to understand is that we have been let down by a lot of guys we thought were the good guys. so it kinda feels like you donâ€™t exist right now. 
assuming you do exist, please be quiet. this is the time for you to listen. not feel attacked (unless you did something that warrants it, in which case read para 1), not indulge in virtue-signalling, not try and include yourself in the conversation.
women are angry, and this is the rage of centuries. we carry rage for what has been done to us, rage we have inherited from countless other women before us, rage we have borrowed from countless other women who donâ€™t have a voice. 
listen to us. stand behind us. amplify our voices. 
examine yourself, your own past, your own conditioning. examine the men around you and talk to them. talk about what needs to change. stop ignoring bad behaviour.
but donâ€™t expect applause for doing the bare minimum, donâ€™t expect a cookie for not being an asshole. donâ€™t make this about you. 
just shut up and listen.
- aishwarya subramanyam @otherwarya .

pedophile and south punjab. 
the land of once some great sufis like 'hazrat ghulam fareed' and many more. is now just a mental asylum, i would say. where jirgas decide the fate of the raped children. hundreds of children are physically raped everyday; and a group of so called elders, set this issue over some money. the purity of a beautiful soul is compromised on mere money, the culprits roam around in every street of the village with pride and people here treat that culprit like a pure soul. just because it was not their child raped. maybe their children are also victim of this. it is now normal here, people know that this happens with many children, some even see it happening with there own eyes; yet they choose to stay silent. this place has turned into sick, numb society. the children then grow up and do the same with other children and the cycle goes on. the land of sick mental retards needs to be fixed, and it needs some serious attention. let us not turn ourselves into those same mentally retarted animals or the country will turn into a asylum. 
many children talked to me aged 6-10. i try to help them the way i can. .
.
.
.

#breakingnews #guatemala 
@realamericannews the group of around 4,000 migrants overpowered police first in tecun uman, guatemala, to make their way over the short bridge into ciudad hidalgo in mexican's southernmost state of chiapas. â£
â£
they had been forced to retreat and reorganize earlier in the day after being met with strong resistance. â£
â£
after crossing the bridge, they were confronted by a daunting force of armed mexican officers who threw tear gas in their direction and stood in lines, lifting up children who ran towards them and standing firm behind their shields. â£
â£
after a standoff, they agreed they would let some of the migrants through and started asking that they form lines.â£
â£
they plan to allow women and children into the country first. â£
â£
the decision flies in the face of president trump's plea to mexican officials on thursday to put an end to the caravan's progress. â£
â£
though the state department and mexican officials have agreed on a plan to shelter any of the migrants who make asylum claims in shelters, their decision to let them carry on north on friday sends them marching on towards the us.â£
â£

text:
they say beauty is in the eye of the beholder.
my eyes are the reflection to my inner soul, people tell me they see my emotions just by the look of my eyes 
i always wondered if they could see my inner kaos and pain and suffering from being abused, sometimes i wonder if i will ever find myself again, the real me and not just the shadow of my own being.
i don't think people realize how hard it is to  be lost and being transformed into your abusers idea of a perfect person, how hard it is to forget the person you once were and then try to find yourself again. 
i try to fit in, be the best me but i still search for my old soul to come back and i really hope she does cause that version of me before my abuser was an awesome little girl who kicked ass.. i will never forget that girl and one day i know she will be back where she belongs, in my mind and heart â¤â¤â¤ #womenrise #survivor #women #abuse #domesticviolencesurvivor #domesticviolenceawareness #domesticviolence #metoo #kickass #strongwomen #nevergiveup #sweden #wetoo #waytosuccess #womenrisesweden #womensbest #womensupportwomen #strongwomenrocks

(although i did get nude in the co-ed sauna in germany with no uncomfortableness but the germans are just cool like that.) because iâ€™ve pretty much always been single, iâ€™ve always had my own back, especially while traveling. i love the wandering and getting lost of travel but there are certainly moments of high alert, especially for me and my curious tendencies. to be honest, i have moments of high alert in my own city, it doesnâ€™t have to only be while traveling. as a single/solo woman, certain experiences will just differ compared to someone being there with you, not bad by any means, just different. being solo can actually be beneficial in some instances but as we all know, most definitely with the recent #metoo movement, we as women still have work to do. so needless to say, to be in a womanâ€™s only facility where every aspect about being a woman is comfortable, respected and welcomed to spend as much time as needed was freaking amazing and on some next level relaxation. even if across the world, iâ€™m so happy these spaces still exist. i highly recommend these experiences to truly get in touch with our feminine energy, a way to connect with our women ancestors who were partaking in the same rituals many moons ago and iâ€™m so excited to continue on these types of journeys. true wellness in a modern world. ğŸ™ŒğŸ»

text:
this #inktober2018 piece is a little close to my heart. it's not the art in itself but the emotion that i am trying to convey through it. #guarded #breakable â¡ï¸ swipe to see the alternate version 
the design community and india as whole is seeing a surge in the number of women coming out with their #metoo stories. it is disheartening to see the numbers but i'm so proud of each of you who have finally decided to stand up for yourselves. it's never too late, 1month or 10years, a perpetrator needs to be called out and held accountable.

as women the only thing we need to realise that we are stronger together. i will support in any way that i can to help you out. props to @nairswapna @mirafmalhotra @vidwhoshe and every person who is helping with the current situation

text:
(sambungan dr catatan 5) keputusan akhir, maka diambil jalur damai. dengan pertimbangan masa depan keluarga tob dan menjaga nama ku dan keluarga dimasyarakat.
dengan berat hati kami berdamai, ada beberapa perjanjian diantaranya adalah bahwa tob tidak akan menjumpai aku tanpa ijin dari kakakku.
hari itu hari minggu, hari paling kelabu. tak berhenti aku menangis. kakak membawa ku ke rumah sakit dan membersihkan semua lukaku disana. 3 hari aku dirawat. lalu aku diantar ke kota a sebelum kedua kakakku pergi pulang ke kota c.
dengan segala puing-puing yang tersisa, aku kembali sekolah. jiwaku benar-benar sakit, batin ku terluka. seharusnya aku butuh orang lain untuk bicara pemulihan ku. tapi siapakah yang peduli?
dua bulan kemudian tob datang ke kota a, dia mencariku ke sekolah dan kerumah kost. saat itu aku memutuskan pindah sekolah. kota a tidak aman lagi bagiku. aku telepon kakakku di kota c, memberitahu keputusanku, mereka akan cari sekolah bagiku. aku pun mengurus surat pindah. 
surat pindah sudah ditangan ku.
aku pulang ke kampung, minta ijin pada orang tua dengan alasan yang ku manipulasi. aku tidak mau ibu sakit, jika ibu tau yang sebenarnya. ibu ku sangat marah. karena sekolah ku saat itu adalah sekolah terbaik di kota a. wajar ibu marah, karena dia tidak tau. kakakku datang ke kampung untuk menjemputku. sekolah yang ku tuju di kota c belum juga ditemukan. karena saat itu (kls 3 sma) sudah selesai pendataan daftar pengikut un. sekolah di kota c tidak ada lagi yang menerima ku. surat pindah sudah ditangan ku. ibu marah-marah. aku putus asa. aku merasakan kesedihan yang sngt dalam. jika aku tidak sekolah maka aku tidak akan jadi apa-apa di masa depan.
aku pergi keladang saat menjelang siang itu, orang tua pergi ke pesta. aku meminum racun rumput yang ada diladang. "tuhan, jika engkau tidak mau mengambilku, akulah yang datang. tidak ada lagi yang baik didunia ini" (lanjut ke catatan 7)

itâ€™s been a minute since i introduced myself, and there are lots of new faces here! so hey there!
.
a bit about me that you may not yet know:
i have my masterâ€™s in nutrition from the university of bridgeport, and iâ€™ve been passionate about health for a long time. when i was still just a tween i was diagnosed with an autoimmune disease. from there, my curiosity about the interaction between our bodies and their environments (including diet environment, stress, sleep, hormones, etc) has grown and grown. iâ€™m currently working towards earning my cns (certified nutrition specialist) title which is a nationally recognized credential for superior nutrition care.
.
i am most passionate about helping women to resolve hormone, gut, and autoimmune related issues through nutrition and lifestyle interventions. i recently shared my own personal story of sexual assault, and i know that a lot of the women i serve have experienced similar trauma. it is my goal to offer support to these women and help them to feel heard â€“ too often, womenâ€™s stories are dismissed. in my nutrition clinic, i believe women. there is a lot we are able to accomplish together by addressing some of the physical manifestations of stress and trauma (ie reduced digestion, gut dysbiosis, nutrient insufficiencies, circadian rhythm disruption, etc.).
.
in addition to seeing nutrition clients virtually all over the us, i also develop recipes and write a blog. my first blog post was published sept of last year (my very own â€œpumpkin truffle chia pudding recipeâ€) and iâ€™ve continued to publish articles several times a month since then (#linkinbio). my most recent blog post is â€œthe truth about chocolate & choosing the best, most ethical raw cacaoâ€.
.
iâ€™m mn born-and-raised (although iâ€™m a recent transplant to boston) and iâ€™d describe my personality as friendly and outgoing, but tbh i think iâ€™m an extroverted-introvert â€“ i love spending time alone going for walks, reading, watching netflix, etc. and i find that i need to â€˜rechargeâ€™ after spending time socializing. oh, and if youâ€™ve taken the #fourtendencies quiz iâ€™m a questioner (basically, i always need to know why).
.

text:
#metoo is probably the biggest movement of our times, but if you really look at it closely, it is history repeating itself with a different name. from the women's march on versailles to the suffragettes movement to #timesup, it has all been about converting the voices of millions of women across the planet into one single voice so that maybe, maybe it would loud enough to shake the earth and cause some change. the art of momentum is something we have learnt very well now. you can push us down but we'll rise back up with a different name, and one day or another, you will have to hear us.

i show myself to know myself,
i show for the earth from which i came,
my prayer is for you to do the same.â€ - @aylanereo ğŸ’›

one of my favourite meditative practices is spending time naked in nature - be it at the beach, in the forest or the ocean. preferably alone. i feel so at ease and in my element... i make a point to do so year-round, regardless of the temperature, time of day and weather. itâ€™s primal, deeply grounding and revitalizing. ğŸ’›

the one thing that keeps me from practicing this form of meditation as often as iâ€™d like to, is fear. not that of wild animals, weather or drowning... but of men. those who perceive my self-expression as an implicit invitation. itâ€™s not. never was and never will be. ğŸ’›

this is one of the reason i love @burningman and the affiliate events - a culture that is deeply rooted in consent. i remember my first time biking solo in the desert - half naked, in the middle of the night, surrounded by thousands of strangers... i felt more safe at that moment than i do in a winter parka in my â€œfriendly neighbourhoodâ€ on a monday evening... each time i go to bm itâ€™s deeply therapeutic - a week of embodying my physical form with no subconscious fear. i never even realized how much mental and emotional energy goes into â€œkeeping myself safe from menâ€ on the daily bases until my first burn. it was eye opening... and infuriating... i felt angry about all of the wasted energy and the toll that it takes on my nervous system... this is not to say that there have never been any assaults at bm, unfortunately, there have been... but this has not been my experience. ğŸ’›

text:
time doesnâ€™t heal, nor does it forget. the wounds only go as deep as the trauma. time says, it will be fine. but it cannot justify what iâ€™ve been through. sometimes, i canâ€™t sit still. sometimes, i donâ€™t sleep, i stay awake with the insects that breeds in my light. but i do cry, for hours. if my tears were raindrops, it would flood the earth. sometimes i wish it did. i curse time then, for coming in disguise as an old friend. and, i, so warmly invited it in, with no control of what it will take from me. iâ€™m robbed of my sense of right or wrong, as the wave of a haunting abusive past sweep through me. i never acknowledged that it came in exchange of my peace. strength. happiness. maybe i was petrified. frozen. constantly taken to a life, which i had carefully tugged away in a penseive. but time, my old friend, make sure that i forget none of it. it is as fresh as the present. it is a painful battle of purging. where i am boxed in a dark place with my grief. until i own my past. until it becomes hope. hope that iâ€™m no longer a prisoner of the nightmares or the eyes that haunt me at daylight. it leaves hope for love. to a tomorrow where i can wake up and breathe without heaviness. today, i wake up everyday with that hope, not to forget, but to remember.

â€¢
i lose faith for a while and then, the incurable romantic and optimist i am, i see beauty again ğŸŒº

new app to offer sexual abuse victims in the fashion industry free counseling. in the wake of the #metoo and #timesup movements, many fashion professionals have broken the silence about the prevalence of sexual misconduct in the fashion industry. last year alone, bruce weber, mario testino and terry richardson, three of the most prestigious photographers in the industry, were accused of sexual abuse.

however, despite the increased public awareness, the issue remains widespread and many victims are too embarrassed to talk to about it. to try and tackle the problem, @humansoffashionf has developed an app to provide victims with free assistance. specifically targeted at fashion professionals, the tool connects victims of sexual harassment and abuse to volunteer therapists and attorneys

text:
new app to offer sexual abuse victims in the fashion industry free counseling. in the wake of the #metoo and #timesup movements, many fashion professionals have broken the silence about the prevalence of sexual misconduct in the fashion industry. last year alone, bruce weber, mario testino and terry richardson, three of the most prestigious photographers in the industry, were accused of sexual abuse.

however, despite the increased public awareness, the issue remains widespread and many victims are too embarrassed to talk to about it. to try and tackle the problem, @humansoffashionf has developed an app to provide victims with free assistance. specifically targeted at fashion professionals, the tool connects victims of sexual harassment and abuse to volunteer therapists and attorneys

#metoo #timesup #sexualabuse #fashionindustry #awareness #harassment #humansoffashion #kristinaromanova #antoniettecosta #protection #harassment #models #newyork #fashionunited

text:
this week my book is going to be published. i found my courage to write my motivational tool book, and it's just 3 days away from being out there.

on thursday the readers, of don't hold back, will be sharing my journey and how i turned my life around to become the entrepreneur i am today. i share how i moved away from a life that was making me sad, a life that was breaking me and a life that brought me night terrors, eating disorders, addictions, complications and much sadness. how i couldn't make a decision, was to scared to walk into a room full of people, and thought everyone hated me. how i would use my addictions to get me through my darkest moments and to help me cope with the sexual abuse i endured from acquaintances as a child and the abandonment of my biological father when i was 11 years old.

through a lifetime of therapists i have learnt who i am, what i need and who is important to my life. i have found my own strength, power and passions and owe my life to many many people, friends, colleagues and family. 
my journey has take many twists and turns, but as i faced negativity during my younger years, i have faced positivity as an adult with much more support and strength. everything is a journey for us all, there are many challenges for us all, nothing worth having is worth having without hard work. i know i am not alone in my story and i don't claim to know everything. everything is relative. i want to reach out and support anyone who feels they need a little more hope, belief and support. 
as a child i know how insecure and vulnerable i was, terrified of so much. but now, i am using my fear to strengthen who i am and i face my fear with confidence, because i know i always had a voice.....i just know how to use it now.

text:
to all of our wow readers, contributors and partners:

one of our goals at wow magazine is to highlight the experiences that women share, to start important conversations and empower our readers. in the world of women, the #metoo movement in all of its global iterations is at the crux of every conversation. and it is time for us to take an active part in the dialogue. wow would like to give you a platform to share your #metoo stories. if you have faced explicit sexual harassment at work by a superior, if you have been taken advantage of at a party by a friend. if you have found yourself in a vulnerable position because of your gender and/or sexuality by a male superior or counterpart. let us know. change begins with a single voice, and nepal too must reckon with our version of sexist power dynamics in society. 
you are welcome to share this post, to spread it to as many women as possible.

to share your story, you can contact the following number on viber, whatsapp or phone-- 98032644310.

#metoo

text:
in the woke of #metoo movement, i was compelled to write this. a lot of women are coming forward and saying, one must have slapped the culprit then and there. the real question is how many and how many times? 
harassment is a part of girlâ€™s and womenâ€™s daily life; from commuting in public transport (a bus), feeling a guy forcing his penis from behind. 
to waiting on the bus stands, being a target of those lecherous eyes. 
to sitting in a local train with closed thighs, if not was that an invite? 
to being rubbed against a manâ€™s shoulder several times, in broad daylight. 
to standing in the locals and feeling hands moving up and down your waistline. 
to walking in a crowded market and listening, â€œà¤…à¤°à¥‡à¤®à¥ˆà¤¡à¤® à¤¨à¥‡ à¤¬à¥œà¥€ à¤›à¤¾à¤¤à¥€ à¤«à¥à¤²à¤¾ à¤°à¤–à¥€ à¤¹à¥ˆ!â€ what is your problem, bhai?

the stories above are so normalised that they wonâ€™t even make it a part of the #metoo movement, even if itâ€™s about time. 
if you do share, people will say, now, why? 
why do we expect a woman to be rani laxmi bai, all the time? 
safe living/working/walking/breathing/talking spaces are every individualâ€™s right.

text:
ever since we were kids, someoneâ€™s always telling us how to dress, how to behave, what to expect from the future and what kind of women we need to be. but we need to start admitting to ourselves that we cannot, will not and should not be expected to become these perfect superwomen that can juggle everything without any help. a corporate career with kids means help at home, be it from family members, spouses or nannies. and if you donâ€™t have children and you have career youâ€™re still being held to these really high expectations of having kids one day(because everyday someone will ask â€œdonâ€™t you want kids?!) and expectations that you have all this free time in your hands because you donâ€™t have kids so youâ€™re supposed to be president by now.

we must take it a little easier on ourselves and ask ourselves the question â€œwhat do i really want and what should i really be achieving that wonâ€™t tear me down as a person?â€. be good and kind to yourself. it all starts there. you canâ€™t help others, you can fully give yourself and add value to your community if youâ€™re not healthy in your mind and soul.
.
.
.
.
#icantdoitall #women #men #equality #life #instadaily #instagood #speakup #metoo #nojudgement

text:
"the balance is already shifting; force is losing its dominance, and mental alertness, intuition, and the spiritual qualities of love and service, in which woman is strong, are gaining ascendancy. hence the new age will be an age less masculine and more permeated with the feminine ideals, or, to speak more exactly, will be an age in which the masculine and feminine elements of civilization will be more evenly balanced." -abdulbaha-

my name is erfan daliri and i'll be your guest selector for the week... i am an eco-feminist, environmental activist and human rights advocate working in social change consultancy social justice campaign management.

i use my own writing and speaking opportunities to advocate for an end to domestic violence, for gender equality, and for the onus to be on us to educate men to develop emotional literacy and move beyond a culture of violence.

as a male i do not speak on behalf of other genders, or even on behalf of the male gender, but as a human being i can certainly speak up for justice, peace, equality and basic human rights for all.

i'm here to call out the mansplaining, to point out the male fragility that causes violence and to end the gender bias and the suppression of any gender, class, creed or culture. 
as a human race we need peace, we need equality, we need justice, and we need all the of us to work together in solidarity. 
i'm honoured to be your guest selector for the week look forward to some awesome conversations. 
peace,
@erfandaliri

text: "it's not very easy to grow up into a woman. we are always taught, almost bombarded, with ideals of what we should be at every age in our lives: "this is what you should wear at age twenty", "that is what you must act like at age twenty-five", "this is what you should be doing when you are seventeen." but amidst all the many voices that bark all these orders and set all of these ideals for girls today, there lacks the voice of assurance. there is no comfort and assurance. i want to be able to say, that there are four things admirable for a woman to be, at any age! whether you are four or forty-four or nineteen! it's always wonderful to be elegant, it's always fashionable to have grace, it's always glamorous to be brave, and it's always important to own a delectable perfume! yes, wearing a beautiful fragrance is in style at any age." ğŸ’ğŸ‘¸ğŸ½âœ¨#yoursistersspace @ayushikejriwal

text:
*long post warning*

not gonna lie, this semester is kicking my butt. i don't really talk about this stuff on social media, i just post pictures i think are cool so people who are flipping through their feed remember that i exist. âœŒ but i feel like this might be important or helpful for someone to hear, so here goes. 
right now, gpa is in a toilet, financial aid is breathing down my neck, family that keeps asking why i don't call anymore, and my anxiety and depression have gotten so bad that i don't have energy to go eat in the caf, much less go to classes. i've been praying so much that god would throw me a life preserver, because i just feel like i'm drowning. i know i've been blessed with so many things, like getting to go to college, having wonderful friends, and family back home that are just a phone call away- and it breaks everything in me to know that i'm completly blowing it. 
it's funny. there are sunsets every day- obviously. we may not even notice them because we're inside sipping coffee, driving home from work, talking to our friends or some other thing. but each one is completly different. in all of creation, there have never been two identical sunsets. the stars are never in the exact same place, or the clouds or the colors because of the different seasons... which is why i love looking at the sky: the stars, the rain, snow, clouds, lightning, the thunder... they're ever changing. his creation is so beautiful and we so often miss it. if god puts that much care into the sky, imagine how much he put into us. i'm not going to pretend that everything is okay right now. but i know that it will be, and that this isn't over. 
on that note, if anyone is in the same boat, please feel free to reach out to me. i know it sucks, but you're not alone.

text:
my journey to love, #metoo
â€¢
this autumn, my dear friend asked me to name god. the first sounds i heard were â€œthe wave.â€ â€œoh thatâ€™s it,â€ i said, â€œthe wave.â€ â€¢
thereâ€™s a moment, when the healing journey stops, and all thatâ€™s left is to be of service. it happened to me this equinox. after years of trying to attain something from my head, after years of feeding my spiritual ego, after years of spiritually bypassing what needed to be loved, i stopped. i stopped competing with the universe. i stopped acting as a casting director for my soulmate. i stopped barfing on people with spiritual bs and let them have their process. i stopped kickin it with people wanting a popularity contest with other insecure people. i stopped. â€¢
i became a hermit. and took a vow of celibacy. for months, i sat with myself and whenever a feeling came up that needed to be loved, i loved it. i loved it all. the heartbreak, the pain, the abuse, the guilt, the shame, all of it. sometimes i would sit all day with a feeling. and other times, i sat for a minute or so. but each time was the same: i sat with myself, gave myself permission to feel, and see myself and that emotion through with love each and every time. and you know something, something miraculous began to happen. i began to develop an intimacy within myself that i had never had before. and each time this intimacy deepened, the wave got closer and closer to me. until finally, one day, the wave approached me, it touched my heart, and it took me out, and i allowed for it to keep taking me. â€¢
i write here and offer this practice of self-love, because it became my liberator. the pain transformed me; victimhood fell away; any notion of any predator, fell away. the only thing that was left was love. i had no choice but to choose love. â€¢
today, i donâ€™t get triggered. and when someone is triggered by me, i am very aware that it is because of their own conditioning. and because i love myself, i have no choice but to love the one who is triggered. ((ğŸ‘‡continue story in comments below))

favorite foods: he has a horror of moist foods so all foods are either dry or liquid - nothing in between. fortunately thereâ€™s cheese, fruits and veggies in dried, delicious forms!

charisma: will smile,
take anyoneâ€™s finger in an inescapable grip and lead them...away and most people just follow him? stops traffic regularly at supermarkets. sometimes we get free stuff.

mamaâ€™s status: happy! most of the time! tired sometimes but treasuring even the toddler tears and tantrums. it is a privilege to be the mama of such a sweet smart little dude! i canâ€™t wait for the next chapter to unfold and i hope heâ€™s having as much fun so far as i am...

the incidents mentioned below are true and happened with a friend. any names of the persons/places mentioned have been changed to protect the victimâ€™s identity. -
i was about 7 when i had my first encounter with sexual harassment. he was my seniorâ€™s younger brother. we used to go to the same school and i was good friends with his brother. he must have been in his pre-teens. i liked being around him and used to play with him. he lived near my house so we used to take the same bus back home from school. 12-13 year olds having a mobile phone weâ€™re consider a rarity in those days and he had just gotten one. one day, while waiting to go back home, i saw him in the bus alone. my naive self thought to give him some company. i went inside the bus and saw that he was playing with something. i didnâ€™t know what it was and he was making weird faces. he noticed me and called me, i felt something was odd so i quickly made a silly excuse and left the bus. the next day, he came and sat by me in the bus and asked me that what did i see yesterday. i asked him what he meant. he smirked and said, â€œwell, i was playing with thisâ€, pointing to his dick. he asked me if i wanted to play with it as well and grabbed my hand to touch him there. i didnâ€™t know what was right or wrong but i started crying. it was a crowded bus and i couldâ€™ve yelled. he saw my face and hushed me and immediately got up from the seat and left. itâ€™s only later when i realized that he was masturbating. i was horrified and told this to my friend, who ended up telling my parents. i was ashamed and thought it was my fault. my parents complained the school authorities and to the police, which later led to his suspension. i felt terrified because i belonged to a middle class family where such incidents could bring us shame but iâ€™m glad my parents reacted immediately. since then, neither i saw him nor his brother who was a genuinely nice person. i lost two good friends. -
a couple of years later, my first cousin and i were home alone and were looking for games to play. we decided on ghar and ghar and he told me that weâ€™d be playing husband and wife.

text:
#metoo - post 2
.
in my first post, i talked about why many women donâ€™t speak up. sometimes, thereâ€™s no explainable reason & thatâ€™s okay! there is no shame in it!â¤ï¸
.
but we live in a society thatâ€™s conditioned to question a victimâ€™s actions before the perpetrators. that is something to be ashamed about! and thatâ€™s what i wanna talk about today...
.
the photo above is from zoukout 2010 in singapore. itâ€™s a 12-hour concert where some of the best djs from across the world play. there were 30,000 people at siloso beach. we got there at 7 pm & stayed till 8 am since guetta & tiesto were playing their sets around 4/5 am. we were young with no kids & had the energy for this!
.
one molestation case took place here & the guy was arrested the very next day. 
now read thisğŸ‘‡ -
â–ªï¸when news broke out, no newspaper article mentioned if the girl was wearing a bikini or shorts or some crazy concert outfit.
â–ªï¸no politician asked what was she doing late night at a concert.
â–ªï¸people didnâ€™t discuss if she was drunk given there was a bar every 50 meters at the concert.
â–ªï¸no one asked how many boys was she hanging out with or if she dated in the past.
.
she was touched without her consent & thatâ€™s a crime.
.
â–ªï¸no victim shaming!!!â–ªï¸
.
this is the difference in conditioning. itâ€™s not just done by men. many women do it too. iâ€™m not trying to compare countries here. fact is there are only a handful of places in the world that are actually this safe & equal for women. but should we not constantly try to reach that level safety, mentality & equality?
.
letâ€™s be honest & admit the harsh reality that india is not a safe country. everyone knows it. so why be surprised about so many cases being brought to light?ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
what we should be surprised about is that itâ€™s 2018 & even now, the victimâ€™s life is torn apart & analysed more than the guy who assaulted her.ğŸ˜”
.
and then people question why women donâ€™t report assaults!
.
no one wants their life being brought under the radar. so show support! the focus is not a small number of possible false allegations.
.
itâ€™s about speaking up together!ğŸ¤
______________________________________

text: on october 21st, 2017, i felt trapped in my own life and more depressed than i had ever been. though i may look happy, i forced a lot of smiles through the hallow shell i became. i was forced to dress a certain way, keep my hair long, and my everyday activities were incredibly limited to work, school, and taking care of my abusive partner. on october 21st, 2017, i contemplated suicide or running to the other side of the country. i was in a panic, unsure of where to go or what to do next.  7 trips, 4 tattoos, one pixie hair cut, and some amazing friends later, i am still flying strong with no intention of coming down. on october 21st, 2018, i woke up in my apartment with my amazing boyfriend and thanked god for everyone in my life. one year ago, i wouldnâ€™t have believed you if you told me i would ever be â€œokayâ€, let alone â€œhappyâ€. but here i am, truly becoming the person i want to be. for those of you struggling to find your place, never give up. and for those of you who have found it, celebrate. â¤ï¸

text:
the trauma trained me to believe my worth was less than nothing. when you hear something on repeat so many times, you begin to believe it. â€œyouâ€™re uglyâ€ he would say, â€œyouâ€™re a scrotty dumb bitchâ€, â€œyou waste of skinâ€, â€œyou fat cowâ€, â€œyou are patheticâ€ â€¦ on repeat, year after yearâ€¦ and i took it all, through the tears, the fears, the occasional physical blowsâ€¦ i took his abuse and faked a smile, thinking i could fix â€œusâ€, that it must be my fault he is so mad all the time, that if only i did something better, something more romantic, something more â€¦more â€¦ moreâ€¦ he would stop the torturous words that stabbed through my very soul. but more was never enough, more was my hopes failed, more was lessâ€¦but not for him. more was less than what i deserved! 
see after finally leaving the man that i claimed to love, i realized something. i realized i was never going to be the same person, and that much like the quote about â€œthe cracks let the light inâ€ , i too would let the light in with compassion, empathy, and a humble kindness for others.
that man had three affairs, hit me the day i fell pregnant with my second child, repeatedly verbally slaughtered me, emotionally battered me daily, but he didnâ€™t break me. what he did was give me a foundation to make myself into a better version of me. 
even though every day i have to say â€œitâ€™s okâ€ , and every day i have to convince the little voices of worthlessness that i am indeed worth something, and every day i have to sit back and allow my vulnerabilities to become my strengthsâ€¦ i have come to realize that because of all that i went throughâ€¦i will forever stand up for the little guy, treat others like i want to be treated, stop judging books by covers, share light even in darkness and be a person that wonâ€™t let someone face their struggles alone. my cracks let in my light, my chips add my characterâ€¦and my struggles make me more gentle when it comes to the treatment of others, becausewe never know what someone is facing â€¦so i am just going to keep being kind and let those little voices fade as time ticks by.Â #bekind #goodness #traumasurvivor #women #empowerment #selfcare #selfworth #abusesurvivor #freedom #nomore #metoo

text:
i am often a very literal poet. i rarely use metaphor. i don't feel the need to veil my experience with ambiguity. i was raped and many of my poems speak to that very clearly. however, sometimes metaphorical comparisons are necessary to illustrate the true horror of the experience. this is something i am trying to explore more because i desperately want people to understand. i want people to get how much sexual violence impresses itself onto the soul of a survivor. â€¢â€¢â€¢
this one is called "hot wax." his grip was so tight against my legs 
i felt his soul pressing its impression onto my body like a singet ring on hot wax
sizzling against my skin
i was moldable and burning under his force
my body bearing the permanent indentation of his violation

he roared and whispered and hissed 
hungry for my searing scream
the flames split me apart
scorching against my skin
splitting me open 
the lava burned my insides and turned me to ash 
the blisters left behind are temporary 
but the sounds of his torment are impressed into me
name: Survivors of Sexual Assault

text:
well most of this makes perfect sense...
iâ€™d put a small red flag on the â€˜abusive relationshipâ€™ bit, vile as it that is; itâ€™s domestic abuse. not a #metoo
.
as i understand it the #metoo movement is to do with people using their inordinate position of power to coerce others into sexual favours in lieu of enhanced work prospects.
correct?
read salma hayek/ paltrow vs harvey weinstein where it really snowballed internationally.
.
people would be well advised to read and prevent a lynch mob mentality followed by a trial by social media .
.
a lot of the discussions need to be more nuanced and not all black and white as people would make it. 
if you donâ€™t see that then it would guarantee ruining the #metoo movement, which in itself is an excellent idea whose time has come.
.
your educated and logical opinions are welcome, as are regrettably the rabid ones.
.
ps: this was sent to me on whatsapp by a female friend who seemed to concur.

text:
spam purple hearts if youâ€™re a reader - a moving and unexpectedly funny exploration of friendship and family, shame and forgiveness, michael donkor's debut novel follows three adolescent girls grappling with a shared experience: the joys and sorrows of growing up.

belinda knows how to follow the rules. as a housegirl, she has learned the right way to polish water glasses, to wash and fold a hundred handkerchiefs, and to keep a tight lid on memories of the village she left behind when she came to kumasi.

mary is still learning the rules. eleven-years-old and irrepressible, the young housegirl-in-training is the little sister belinda never had.

amma has had enough of the rules. a straight-a student at her exclusive london school, she has always been the pride of her ghanaian parents until now. watching their once-confident teenager grow sullen and wayward, they decide that sensible belinda is the shining example amma needs.

so belinda must leave mary behind as she is summoned from ghana to london, where she tries to impose order on her unsettling new world. as summer turns to autumn, belinda and amma are surprised to discover common ground. but when the cracks in their defenses open up, the secrets they have both been holding tightly threaten to seep out.

text:
â€˜@teddy_quinlivan - who recently appeared in a louis vuitton campaign and who spoke up about being transgender last fall, was dropped by her new york agency shortly after she posted a statement on instagram about being inappropriately touched on a shoot, and complained to her agents about the perpetrator.
the post was in april, and she was dropped in june â€” an almost unheard-of act for someone included in the list of â€œtop 50â€ models in the world on models.com.
ms. quinlivan said she could not know for sure why she was dropped (and the agency, women management, did not respond to requests for further comment on the subject), but she noted: â€œwhen i talked about being trans, they were very supportive. they were much more hesitant when i talked about assault.â€
when she first raised the issue, â€œthey shrugged off my concerns and told me that this type of behavior was typical of this individual,â€ she said. later, when ms. quinlivan continued to be upset, â€œmy bookers responded to my claims with compassion, but they offered no solutions other than suggest that i not work for the many brands my assailant also worked for.â€ @nytimes on the world of modelling post #metoo - in light of the recent @bostonglobe article arguing that karl temper did not commit assault despite multiple unrelated sources with the same story, are the codes and practices and shows of â€˜effortâ€™ simply just pr mechanisms to protect the worst offenders? do models have a real opportunity to speak out about their abuse when their abusers still hold complete power over them? @nytimes found that the â€˜assault hotlinesâ€™ set up by conde naste, lmvh & kering were never used whereas @modelallianceny received over 100 calls between october 2017 and july 2018 reporting sexual harassment and assault â€” an increase of 40 times over the year before. 
do you think anything much has changed in reality? ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸

text_retweet:
itâ€™s been eight years since south korean prosecutor seo ji-hyun says she was sexually harassed, but itâ€™s still painful to recall. â€œfor a long time, i tortured myself by blaming myself for everything,â€ she tells time in seoul. seo alleges she was repeatedly groped at a funeral by a senior male colleague, while the countryâ€™s justice minister sat nearby, in 2010. seo reported the incident to her managers shortly after, but was subjected to performance audits that she describes as unfair, and assigned to a lower level branch outside seoulâ€”a move she says did not match her strong track record at work. last fall, seo watched as #metoo took off. she began to grasp how widespread sexual harassment and assault were. seo added her voice to the rising global chorus in january, sharing her experience in an open letter on her workplace intranet and signing it with #metoo. within a few hours of posting, she says the justice department said her statement was false and refused to issue an apology. (the ministry of justice did not respond to timeâ€™s repeated requests for comment on the case; seoâ€™s alleged harasser has denied the charge, saying he was too drunk at the time to recall what happened.) that evening, seo spoke on one of south koreaâ€™s most influential news programs. her words resonated: she is widely credited with kick-starting south koreaâ€™s version of the movement. womenâ€™s rights activists and survivors across asia have seen the global reckoning confronting sexual harassment, assault and abuse as a chance to shape their own national conversations about gender #inequality, amid intense backlash and great personal risk. but the broader cultural impact of speaking out in such challenging environments is creating a groundswell of support and solidarity. photograph by @timfranco for time. video by @ariahychen for time

text:
so. i never came out to my family, or close friends. only a few, and far between know the truth.
i am a survivor of child abuse - molestation and much more to be exact. i still remember the nights quite well. i was between the age of 7-8.
when i was 12, nearing thirteen, weird guys would come to our house.
mom didn't know, but a few people she met on the internet would get hands-y with me.
including one night where i was drugged,, and some guy telling me to "lay in bed."
i was scared to tell anyone.
always suffering in silence.
lost my home, and everything that belonged to me. my childhood washed away, ruined by rats and a flood in a barn.
cherished toys, things i wish i still had, like my spyro plushie.
years, i held this all back.
felt ashamed.
hated myself.
didn't have a mom in my life - till she returned and was ripped away from me.
we finally made amends.
and i was starting - well, be okay.
i'm not so sure anymore. i miss her dearly. all of this time, lost.. things i regret.
things i wish she knew. 
after everything that has happened, i stayed strong. sure, i've fallen apart, suffer from depression, anxiety, but somehow, i push through.
i'm a survivor.
i lived through so much.
i'm not ashamed for who i am. what happened to me - against my will.
i'm a stronger person. kinder.
and now, weight has now left my shoulders.
time to start healing; again. 
#metoo
#metoomovement

text: itâ€™s been eight years since south korean prosecutor seo ji-hyun says she was sexually harassed, but itâ€™s still painful to recall. â€œfor a long time, i tortured myself by blaming myself for everything,â€ she tells time in seoul. seo alleges she was repeatedly groped at a funeral by a senior male colleague, while the countryâ€™s justice minister sat nearby, in 2010. seo reported the incident to her managers shortly after, but was subjected to performance audits that she describes as unfair, and assigned to a lower level branch outside seoulâ€”a move she says did not match her strong track record at work. last fall, seo watched as #metoo took off. she began to grasp how widespread sexual harassment and assault were. seo added her voice to the rising global chorus in january, sharing her experience in an open letter on her workplace intranet and signing it with #metoo. within a few hours of posting, she says the justice department said her statement was false and refused to issue an apology. (the ministry of justice did not respond to timeâ€™s repeated requests for comment on the case; seoâ€™s alleged harasser has denied the charge, saying he was too drunk at the time to recall what happened.) that evening, seo spoke on one of south koreaâ€™s most influential news programs. her words resonated: she is widely credited with kick-starting south koreaâ€™s version of the movement. womenâ€™s rights activists and survivors across asia have seen the global reckoning confronting sexual harassment, assault and abuse as a chance to shape their own national conversations about gender #inequality, amid intense backlash and great personal risk. but the broader cultural impact of speaking out in such challenging environments is creating a groundswell of support and solidarity. photograph by @timfranco for time. video by @ariahychen for time

do the #metoo stories make you feel uncomfortable?
how uncomfortable?
just enough to pass them by when you realize the subject matter?
enough to scroll quickly and unfollow those who write their stories?
or does it make you so uncomfortable you realize you have no choice but to aid in change.
â— 
these stories should make you tremble. you should feel hurt in your bones and feel your soul weep.
that is only a fraction of what these warriors have felt. & if you donâ€™t? itâ€™s because youâ€™ve become so accustomed to these stories that youâ€™ve become numb.
â— 
instead of complaining that itâ€™s â€œtoo muchâ€ or that â€œitâ€™s hard to know what the line is anymoreâ€ maybe you should do something a little different.
â— 
instead of trying to have an opinion about someone elseâ€™s experience; instead of deciding how traumatized they are allowed to be; instead of deciding how painful it is/was; instead of minimizing these stories and putting them into a box so you feel less awkward; instead of creating the assumption that they want attention, maybe try this-
1. sit down.
2. shut the fuck up.
3. listen to our story.
4. listen to our cries.
5. hold space.
6. listen to the pain in our words.
7. see the anger in our eyes.
8. feel the fear in our souls.
9. acknowledge our wound.
10. support us as we take our power back.
â— 
& if you arenâ€™t ready to do that, then do everyone a favor and at least follow step 1 & 2.

itâ€™s been eight years since south korean prosecutor seo ji-hyun says she was sexually harassed, but itâ€™s still painful to recall. â€œfor a long time, i tortured myself by blaming myself for everything,â€ she tells time in seoul. seo alleges she was repeatedly groped at a funeral by a senior male colleague, while the countryâ€™s justice minister sat nearby, in 2010. seo reported the incident to her managers shortly after, but was subjected to performance audits that she describes as unfair, and assigned to a lower level branch outside seoulâ€”a move she says did not match her strong track record at work. last fall, seo watched as #metoo took off. she began to grasp how widespread sexual harassment and assault were. seo added her voice to the rising global chorus in january, sharing her experience in an open letter on her workplace intranet and signing it with #metoo. within a few hours of posting, she says the justice department said her statement was false and refused to issue an apology. (the ministry of justice did not respond to timeâ€™s repeated requests for comment on the case; seoâ€™s alleged harasser has denied the charge, saying he was too drunk at the time to recall what happened.) that evening, seo spoke on one of south koreaâ€™s most influential news programs. her words resonated: she is widely credited with kick-starting south koreaâ€™s version of the movement. womenâ€™s rights activists and survivors across asia have seen the global reckoning confronting sexual harassment, assault and abuse as a chance to shape their own national conversations about gender #inequality, amid intense backlash and great personal risk. but the broader cultural impact of speaking out in such challenging environments is creating a groundswell of support and solidarity. photograph by @timfranco for time. video by @ariahychen for time

text:
no means no. .
.
whether it's a stranger, someone you know, a boyfriend, or a spouse. .
.
no means no.
.
.
there is no "under this circumstance" or "scenario" where it's ok for anyone to use their power over you or take advantage of you. it doesn't matter if you know the person or not, you still always have the right to say no.
.
.
don't let anyone tell you otherwise! don't let anyone manipulate you into doing something you don't want to do. that's still just as awful.
.
.
and if something has happened to you, like it did to me, know it wasn't your fault. you said no. you expressed what you wanted & if anyone went beyond that, it's on them. not you.
.
.

text:
access to a full range of tweets on some subjects is increasingly difficult or more expensive.

last month, twitterâ€™s chief executive, jack dorsey,Â toldÂ the senate intelligence committeeÂ he believes â€œthe people use twitter as they would a public square and they often have the same expectations that they would have of any public space.â€ but for all his vows of openness, the platform is making it increasingly difficult and expensive for academics to access tweets to research important questions fromÂ how information about diseases like zika spreadÂ toÂ how social movements like black lives matter workÂ toÂ how social media can be used to promote democracy.

hereâ€™s the problem:Â itâ€™s not possible to use twitterâ€™sÂ advanced search functionÂ to pull all tweets related to a certain subject within a date range. for example, when i tried searching recently for use of the #metoo hashtag during the first three days of theÂ movement, i got a subset of tweets, but not all of them, and there was no way for me to know how many tweets there had been in aggregate. astonishingly, when i searched for use of the #metoo hashtag on oct. 15, 2017 â€”Â the first day of the movement â€”Â i got zero results.

and twitterâ€™s policies have made it increasingly challenging and costly for academics like me to access historical tweets in other ways.

justin littman, a software developer at stanford university libraries, explained that researchers with advanced software skills used to be able to sign up to write their own software and get the data they needed from twitterâ€™s application programming interface (api). in july, the companyÂ announcedÂ that researchers would have to first request access to the api for such projects order to prevent malicious use of the application.
.
.
source:  kara alaimo is an assistant professor of public relations at hofstra university and author of â€œpitch, tweet, or engage on the street: how to practice global public relations and strategic communication.â€ she previously served in the obama administration. for blomberg. .

text_retweet:
dear paul boise:  perhaps the reason amy schumer 'never seems to shut up about body- image, ' as you so elegantly put it, is because, as tina fey puts it, "now every girl is expected to have caucasian blue eyes, full spanish lips, a classic button nose, hairless asian skin with a california tan, a jamaican dance hall ass, long swedish legs, small japanese feet, the abs of a lesbian gym owner, the hips of a nine-year-old boy, the arms of michelle obama, and doll tits." but wait, paul. there's more! have you ever heard of sonya renee taylor, roxanne gay, jes baker, megan jayne crabbe, alph and syl ko, or tarana burke? they are just some of the other women who won't shut up about body- positivity. i think it might be because women have been told by a society run by patriarchal aholes since the dawn of the herding culture that started 10,000 years ago that their bodies, voices, and ideas are wrong.  that they must change something in some way about their bodies to be deemed 'valuable' by said patriarchs. 
and maybe, paul,  the fact that women are told at every turn today; right now-- every time they open their phones, walk down the street,  look at a magazine, watch television, go to a movie, or drive by a billboard, to name but a few examples--- that their bodies need to change in some way if they are to be pleasing to the racist, sexist patriarch, maybe, paul, that's why amy and many other nasty women won't shut up about body- image. 
and maybe, paul, you should shut the fck up and read something other than maxim before you write another 'insightful' article about a subject you only seem to understand through the lens of subjectivity. 
love, 
women everywhere.

text:
i return from #wastelandweekend a changed woman. i live, i die. i live again. witness me!
.
iâ€™m starting off this post w/a film quote, but i'm not kidding: i caught a sexual predator at wasteland. a sexual predator w/a history who was preying on me.
.
heâ€™s an instructor at a local prestigious university. he was my teacher and held a position of power. he offered a lodging arrangement that i accepted b/c i got signed onto wasteland last-min and needed a ride. he never got to touch me. instead, i opted out and confronted him. b/c three authority figures independently reported that i was in an unsafe situation, this man was banned and immediately removed from the premises.
.
but this isnâ€™t over b/c i am going to be the last woman he'll ever prey upon.
.
i may seem timid, but that's b/c i bide my time and take it all in before i show my cards. i might seem gullible b/c iâ€™m an eager learner, but i know when i'm being fucked over. i can see how someone in a privileged position to offer me knowledge can withhold it to manipulate me. but i choose to be vulnerable so i can connect w/ the people who cherish me instead of exploiting my openness.
.
i grew up in brooklyn, a crucible of 1st/2nd-gen asian american immigrants in competition for spots in elite schools. i eschewed anything feminine so as not to appear weak. i rejected everything that made me seem like a stereotypical petite asian girl so there would be no excuse to treat me like one. i had to be extraordinary to get accepted into the ivy league on grants+scholarships; so i became an arrogant little shit who acted like it. but i also suffered from undiagnosed bipolar ii depression and couldn't trust other people. i refused to accept help. i am who i am today b/c i don't care if i resemble the prey that older white men tend to target. b/c if you try to fuck w/ me, the mean new yorker oliviaâ€”who can now deadlift 200 lbsâ€”will come out and seek justice.
.
i am changed by the people who advocated for me and accepted me into the ems community. i am changed b/c i now know how to recognize sexual predators and what it takes to bring them down. you can too. #metoo #timesup #believesurvivors #thankyoudrford

text:
iâ€™ve spoken on what #overcomingfriendlyfire is, but i would also like to go on the record and say what it is not. â€œas years pass, some details fade, while others remain etched throughout my entire being. the account given is to the best of my recollectionâ€”from my point of view. i have no intention of identifying or demonizing the people who have played a part in harming me. in fact, iâ€™ve taken great care to leave out certain details to protect themâ€”more than what they have done for me. and there are just some details i will not share in the book to protect those who may read it from being triggered. 
i share these pictures of my dad, pastor michael bradford, because he and my mom came to my rescue. iâ€™ll never forget him saying â€œiâ€™ve never seen someone have so much compassion for a person who has hurt them like this.â€ i have no malice or ill will towards any of the individuals. i donâ€™t know why god made me this way, but he did. and to be honest, it has been extremely difficult, and sometimes i donâ€™t want to, but from time to time i hold on to his strength to pray for them, to forgive. to release. 
i am not perfect. i have been the cause of othersâ€™ pain. at different stages in my life, someoneâ€™s blood has been on my hands. i believe in extending the same grace and mercy i request of my savior, and just hope and pray that my fellow humans, being, will see fit to forgive my trespasses against them. [sonder (n.) the realization that each random passerby is living a life as vivid and complex as your own.] this does not excuse my behavior or actions, nor does it excuse those who waged war against me. but maybe, just maybe, it will help us work through it.â€ -jamie c. tchakoua, excerpt from overcoming friendly fire #metoo #believesurvivors

text:
the past 40 days have taught me so very much about myself. they have taught me how my politics don't always protect me from my feelings. i'm learning how to not cloak my vulnerabilities. i'm also learning to navigate my intellect with more care. 
i have not travelled anywhere for over a year and now i've been on the road for 40+ days (not counting my time in murica). i have had immense privilege to experience vast sunsets & the kindnesses of various strangers. but many of these sunsets have been lonely and the many strangers have brought their own anxieties with them. 
managing my mental & physical illnesses have taken a whole different toll on me.  it's easy to assume i'm doing okay based on my stories (and i sometimes encourage that image). but there's a lot of work involved in even getting out of bed or talking to strangers. i've had many breakdowns. listening to stories from women in the ongoing #metoo movement in india particularly took a massive toll for a week. not that i would have it any other way.

but journaling helps. maintaining a mental health journal has been a constant source of comfort and it helps me examine myself in different situations. i'm here to help anyone struggling with journaling or travelling with mental illnesses. i'm no expert, but if a few tips/listening ear can help anyone - i'm happy to support them.

text:
a beautiful message from a friend here in mÃ©xico city ğŸ‡²ğŸ‡½! our wounds are teachers that allow growth and new beginnings. .
.
we think of wounds as bad.  we want them to heal right away.  we rather not face them.  we rather not even create space for the wound to exist within our being.  in turn, we reject our wounds and suppress them.  we think by suppressing them we can make them disappear...
.
.
but they donâ€™t.  they persist within you guiding your behavior in unconscious ways that create the life that unfolds before you... seemingly by chance.... but it isnâ€™t, because the internal wounds ask for attention in other ways.  you pick fights.  you are impatient.  you suffer from anxiety.  panic attacks.  depression.  these are all the voices of your wounds asking to be heard.  open the crack and let the light in to heal you more deeply than could have ever happened if the wound didnâ€™t exist.
.
.

.
if you reframe your wounds this way, what does that do for you?  how could that help you live in your authenticity?
.
.
because you are everything, my child.  you are you.  you are your wounds.  and you are perfectly imperfect.  welcome back all the pieces of you that you have shunned, rejected, and avoided. with heart. ğŸ’“
.

text:
it *never* feels like a good time to tell my #metoo story. my excuses? i was spared from what could have been. i know your story is likely much worse, and i want to be sensitive to that.
. 
i share my story so that you can share yours. so you know itâ€™s not your fault. so this hopefully stops altogether. and so men in power know that weâ€™re not having this s*%t anymore! ğŸ’ªğŸ¼
. 
i studied abroad in cortona, italy the summer of 2010.
. 
after dinner one night, i walked up the stairs with some friends to a patio.
. 
and there he was.
. 
a super large man who looks like the brawny lumberjack. i had never, no not once, spoken to this professor.
. 
i introduced myself and we got to talking. we all walked to the lions well pub. as we talked, he started rubbing my legs under the table. ğŸ˜³
. 
i immediately started freaking out!
. 
he asked me to tell him more about myself, so i told him i was so in love with chaz and was definitely marrying him, hoping that would ward him off... hello? ğŸ˜¡
.

text:
i'm learning to accept my flaws and imperfections.

big deal as i am a perfectionist. my flaws would (still do at times) make me feel abnormal and like i was damaged beyond repair. that's what abuse does. mix the damage from years of abuse with low self esteem, and you get an unhealthy, negative self concept. and this just fuels anxiety and depression.

it's taken me years to get to where i am now, all in mind, body and spirit. i'm much more healthier now, but still healing and struggling more than i would like. thank god. that he loves me (and you!) enough to not leave me in my constant suffering. currently i'm working on my mindset and thought life. this is where the battle lies. it's hard. but i'm determined to win.

you can win your battles too. keep moving forward.

still a queen ğŸ‘‘âœŠ.
.
.
.

text:

.
.
the statutory and case law answers vary by location. but the violations are clear... and the damage is devastating.
.
.

text: warrior. it's a word i have associated myself with for a long time now. not only does my name (kelly) mean warrior in gaelic (i have very strong irish roots), but i've been fighting battles in my life for well over a decade. having autoimmune disease and chronic lyme disease has not only left me fighting for my life every day for years, but also battling through chronic pain from other conditions spawning from these illnesses as well as emotional hardship, too. when you live with severe, ongoing, chronic pain every single day, just having the courage to wake up the next day and fight through it again is an amazing accomplishment in itself. when there isn't any medication or therapy to bring you any relief, and you continue on suffering daily, doing everything you can get your hands on to try to heal yourself, that makes you a warrior. it's not about self admiration. it's about empowering yourself, and giving yourself strength to fight again another day. it's a very hard road to walk. you're lucky if you have anyone in your life who remotely understands. so, to all my fellow warriors out there, i am here, cheering you on, supporting you all the way! whether you are battling chronic illness, cancer, mental and emotional illness, domestic violence, or are an assault and abuse survivor, or a mother or father fighting for the health of your child, an lgbtq or other minority fighting for equality, or just a woman trying to make it in this world, we are all warriors in our own ways. that's why, i've teamed up with @ariellasdesigns to give you 10% off of your own warrior sweatshirt! she also makes other great designs and you can use code: warrior10 for anything on her site! they make great gifts, too! it could be an awesome way to show support to a friend or loved one going through a hard time. this cropped sweatshirt is so soft and comfy. it's perfect for days when i don't feel well enough to get dressed up but still want to look cute! be sure to follow @ariellasdesigns and check out all of her amazing designs ğŸ˜Š hold on to hope, my friends. you can't fight this hard for so long and not ever see the other side ğŸ’šğŸ’ª#warrior #lymewarrior #lymedisease
